Subject: CRITICAL: Please Read -- Changes Regarding Your 401K
A webinar regarding these changes is scheduled for Tuesday; October 2 @ 9:00 MST.
Important Information about Your Companys Retirement Plan

Venafi; Inc. (your Employer or we) recently selected ING Life Insurance and Annuity Company as the new investment and service provider for the Venafi; Inc. 401k Plan (the Plan).  All record keeping services will be transferred to ING and all amounts in the investment vehicles currently available under the Plan will be transferred to  new investment options offered through ING; beginning the week of November 12; 2012. A conversion period will make this a successful and seamless transfer; and ensure the accurate and complete transfer of your account and Plan records from our current service provider.

During the conversion period we must undertake several steps to transfer services and plan assets to ING.  Our current provider must finalize our records by completing all transactions currently in process; balance the Plan and forward the records to ING.  Then; ING must update its record keeping system for our Plan provisions; the enrollment record for each participant; and the transaction records supplied by our current service provider.  In addition; ING must receive and allocate our plan assets to the new investment options (as we direct) and balance the records to the assets it receives for our Plan.

This conversion process will begin the week of Sunday; October 28; 2012; and end the week beginning Sunday; December 9; 2012.  During the conversion period your deferred contributions will continue to be deducted from your paycheck and invested according to your direction.  However; to establish accurate records and fund balances with ING; during this period no other individual account transactions can be processed either through our current provider or through ING.  This is referred to as a blackout period.  Specifically during the blackout period; you will not be permitted to:
*	Request a distribution of Plan assets;

Body: Click here to attend: http://www.electric-cloud.com/resources/webinars.php?commid=56915

Sr No: Live webcast: Getting More Out of Your Development Testing
Presenter: David Rosen; Product Manager at Electric Cloud; and Arthur Hicken; Evangelist at Parasoft Corporation

To improve quality and reduce time-to-market; Development Testing techniques such as static code analysis and unit testing are critical for most serious software R&D organizations. Finding and fixing such code while maintaining agility and speed from the earliest phases of the software development lifecycle has been proven to be a very effective (and cost-efficient) way to prevent defects from being shipped in the final product. Learn what techniques are helpful; how they can be easily applied; and how to avoid the most common pitfalls. Join this webinar to hear from thought leaders at Electric Cloud and Parasoft on how your organization can get the most out of development testing.

Subject: Agile Forum :: Open Mic Session
When: Thursday; October 23; 2014 2:30 PM-3:30 PM (UTC) Dublin; Edinburgh; Lisbon; London.

Please attend this Open Mic session with the Agile CoE<http://confluence.ncr.com/display/AgileDev/Agile+Coaches+and+CoE>. This is your opportunity to ask our Agile Coaches about any aspect of Agile software development.
Calls are held each month; with every 3rd month focusing on a chosen Agile Good Practices topic. The format of these sessions is informal and interactive.

Got ideas you want to explore? Got a question on your mind? We want your suggestions / questions in advance – please leave a discussion topic on the Agile Forum<http://confluence.ncr.com/display/AgileDev/NCR+Agile+Forum> page or send to Eddie Durrant<mailto:eddie.durrant@ncr.com?subject=Agile%20Open%20Mic%20input> – and; of course; your input will be welcome on the call (either through WebEx Chat or simply speak out).

We are sending this invite primarily to Scrum Masters; PO's; BA's and servant leaders - please feel empowered to pass this on to anyone we have missed and; of course; Scrum Masters/Team Leaders please forward to your team.

Apologies if the timing doesn’t work for you – we’re accommodating teams from multiple time-zones – but we are varying the day and start time each month to help give everyone a good chance of attending. We will be recording the session and posting it on the Agile Forum<http://confluence.ncr.com/display/AgileDev/NCR+Agile+Forum> page soon after.
Please be prompt – we will be starting within the first few minutes.

Subject: BA Meeting and Consolidated metric thoughts
We posed the question to the BA forum this morning.  I heard  a lot of the same feedback concerns that Doug experienced when this was previously brought up with the team members.
A comment was made that metrics should be on burn down Story points and burn down Business value or; how do we effectively tie the work to Customer satisfaction.
An additional comment was that teams/developers  can get preoccupied with logging time than focusing on doing the work.

As for comparing our estimates against actuals (DONE) the strong opinion was to use Plan view and/or Jira. (Jira Internal Time using “Times and Phases”). This would allow us an indirect way of getting a feel for how much time elapses from when a story is picked up to when it is completed.
If we are able to do this through Jira/plan view then we shouldn’t have the issue of people actually logging time to or through another external program.
And plan view could break out time tasks by Product and Work ID. These were the suggestions by a few people on the forum.

I did get a contact name of a person who is using Jira to gather time spent and I can reach out to that person for more information if this group fells its necessary or maybe we already know this information.

Well; I’ve been trying to get acquainted with this STAR - JIRA<https://intranet.ncr.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=frontpage&Itemid=1845>

Since I just got access to JIRA; I don’t know if this is the same functionality or something different. I was thinking about finding the NCRU Course #74292 to learn a bit more about it and perhaps request user access.
If you think I may be headed up the wrong tree let me know and perhaps a 30 minute level set would be a good use of time.
Below are the features offered by STAR-JIRA
•       Quick search is really quick –based on issue ID or description text
•       Being a web based tool; user does not need to bother about any installation
•       Users now have a Dashboard where they can view the activities on the projects/bugs.
•       JIRA has a facility to add files to bugs and also screenshots.
•       Integrated reporting features: users can generate different types of inbuilt and custom reports through the tool. Reports are based on user designed filters

•       JIRA Issue: Bugs in software; raised either at development stage or after going live OR a discrepancy issue raised by SQA; once documented in JIRA is known as Issue. An issue in JIRA contains all tracking information related to the bug which developers are supposed to enter in JIRA based on the developments done.
•       JIRA Project: A JIRA project is created for an application and is meant to capture all bugs on that.
o       Collection of Issues to achieve a specific outcome
o       Use a unique Project Key (mnemonic) as a reference; e.g. PROJX;DEV
o       Has a single Project Lead
Each NATS Application will have two projects created in STAR-JIRA. For Example ERP will have following two projects.
>       ERP GCA: To track production issues.
•       Projects in STAR-JIRA could have multiple versions.
•       Create version under application; whenever a new development project/PERT is initiated. For example following versions will show up under ERP Project.
•       GCA Projects in STAR-JIRA will have only one version named “GCA”.
o       Sub-categorization of Issues within a Project
o       Each component has a default owner
o       Default component owner is the default assignee of the issue
•       JIRA Filter is a saved search – the Filter includes the criteria used to perform the search; not the search results.
•       JIRA Personal Dashboard is the first page that users see when they login; and contains a number of Gadgets (information elements) that are configurable by the end-user.

I’ll send out a webex at the time the meeting starts.

Body: Update: With the Spyder release coming up; I’m rescheduling the Automation trainings for January.

Sr No: As we discussed during our last Automation sync-up meeting we will be doing a ‘getting started’ training to get us familiarized with the tools available for automation. I know there are releases coming up; so please let me know if this a bad time to schedule this training. This training is meant to lay the foundation for future automation discussions by ensuring we’re all on a similar page.
-       I’ll visit each of you to make sure you have what you need to successfully complete the training
-       An email about the exercise we’ll be covering will be sent out at least a day in advance to give you time to prepare
-       Time to do the exercise [30 mins]
Let me know if you have any questions or won’t be able to make it.

Note: I’ve added Brenda; Taylor and Doug as ‘optionals’ so they are aware of what is going on. I’ll keep doing this in the future so that we can better synchronize automation with the realities of future release work. I’m open to rescheduling if there are conflicts.

Annual Murder Mystery Dinner
Body: Host: jeremy.cornett@venafi.com

Sr No: You are Cordially Invited to Attend the Hidden Council’s Annual Costume Ball; an evening of deceit; treachery & murder. Due to the recent Watcher murders; we will also be holding a Hidden Council meeting at the Ball! If you get lost on the way or are going to be late; please call Jeremy at 385-242-6946.
As a murder mystery participant; you’ll be expected to…
1.   Provide $5 per person (aka $10 a couple) to Jeremy to help purchase the murder mystery kit ($105 cost). Excess money will go to party supplies.

2.   We must wait for everyone to arrive before we can start; so please arrive promptly at 5 PM. Please call if you’re going to be late. If you don’t call; I may have to reassign your character before we can proceed.
3.   Let Jeremy know if you haven’t been emailed your assigned character’s background. Everyone should have received this.
4.   Come prepared with a made up backstory that fits with your provided character; like a story or two; real or fictional. Be ready to ad-lib; a lot!
5.   Come in costume – it’s a masquerade ball so any costume will do! I’ll have a dozen masquerade masks for guests to use if they’d like.
6.   Bring a dish to share as this will be a buffet style dinner consisting of appetizers and desserts.
7.   Have thick skin as the characters may slander each other a bit; or even flirt with one another.
8.   Be prepared to have a great time! These evenings are loads of fun and laughs.

Subject: 1 on 1 :  Rion Carter
Body: Please use the following agenda to prepare for our one on ones:

Sr No: Accomplishments & status - a list of current projects; with one or two sentences describing progress and status on each.
2.      Blocked/Waiting on - a list of roadblocks currently stopping projects from progressing.   Describe the roadblock for each in one or two sentences.
3.      To do - a high-level to-do list of what you would like to accomplish in the next week
4.      Areas to develop - areas of development and what activities you have undertaken to develop in those areas.

5.      Quarterly goal tracking - You should be making steady progress toward fulfilling those goals. This is a place to track that progress. Your monthly; quarterly or yearly goals. Note your progress.
6.      Action plans – Record the results of previously established action plans including whether or not they are complete.
Please come to our meeting prepared.

Subject: Department Demo
Body: Please see the Wiki page for Department Demo guidelines:

Sr No: The purpose of the Department Demo is to engage and inform all of R&D on team progress and projects.  This meeting is a forum for you to learn; view and discuss what is happening in other teams.

Each team will hold their own retrospective; review and planning meetings.  This meeting follows your sprint review meeting with your product's owner.  This meeting is not to be mistaken with your Sprint Review.

The department demo is an optional meeting for all; with the exception of those teams that have finished stories and have demoed them to their product owners.  If the story is accepted as "done" by your product owner; the team must demo the completed stories in the next department demo following the stories being marked as done.
The Department  DEMO meeting will be for the department as a whole to come and view what other teams are working on.
The agenda will be as follows:
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
>       Each team will be required to present a demo and send someone to answer questions for the Q&A
>       Snacks will be provided at this meeting (bagels; doughnuts and/or fruits and veggies.)
>       If your team is not giving a demo due to sprint staggering; please let one of the following know:  Jessica; Brenda; Maria; Taylor; or Doug.
>       Each Demo and Q&A period will be time boxed.  Anything over this time box will be taken offline.
>       Please note that we may not use the whole hour time period as the sprints are staggered.
>       Cell phones are not allowed in the meeting room during this meeting.
>       Product owners; managers; BA’s; and program managers are chickens in this meeting and should behave accordingly.

Subject: Department Demo
Body: Please see the Wiki page for Department Demo guidelines:

Sr No: The purpose of the Department Demo is to engage and inform all of R&D on team progress and projects.  This meeting is a forum for you to learn; view and discuss what is happening in other teams.

Each team will hold their own retrospective; review and planning meetings.  This meeting follows your sprint review meeting with your product's owner.  This meeting is not to be mistaken with your Sprint Review.

The department demo is an optional meeting for all; with the exception of those teams that have finished stories and have demoed them to their product owners.  If the story is accepted as "done" by your product owner; the team must demo the completed stories in the next department demo following the stories being marked as done.
The Department  DEMO meeting will be for the department as a whole to come and view what other teams are working on.
The agenda will be as follows:
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
o       Team Numbers  (this should include committed; actual; unit test coverage & QA #s – test cases created; executed; planned; pass/fail/block rate)
>       Each team will be required to present a demo and send someone to answer questions for the Q&A
>       Snacks will be provided at this meeting (bagels; doughnuts and/or fruits and veggies.)
>       If your team is not giving a demo due to sprint staggering; please let one of the following know:  Jessica; Brenda; Maria; Taylor; or Doug.
>       Each Demo and Q&A period will be time boxed.  Anything over this time box will be taken offline.
>       Please note that we may not use the whole hour time period as the sprints are staggered.
>       Cell phones are not allowed in the meeting room during this meeting.
>       Product owners; managers; BA’s; and program managers are chickens in this meeting and should behave accordingly.

QA Book Club:
Body: Team;  I am moving this meeting to the fourth Thursday of the month instead of Wednesday(sprint planning days).  This meeting is not optional.  Make sure you are prepared and plan around this meeting.

Sr No: This is the meeting for our QA Book Club.  This meeting is a company sponsored opportunity for our team to engage in continuous learning and improvement for our team and our careers.
Team this meeting will no longer be optional.  Plan on attending this meeting once a month and having your work done for the class.
If you do not have one of these books; please let me know asap so that I can purchase this for you.
NOTE:  This meeting is priority and will still occur even if one person cannot attend.
NOTE:  If you have any suggestions for books or topics for QA book club; please send them out to the list.
I would like to suggest the following books (not in any particular order):
How to Break Software:  A practical Guide to testing ( James Whittaker)
Lessons Learned in Software Testing (Cem Kaner; James Back & Bret Pettichord)
Agile Testing:  A Practical guide for Testers and Agile Teams (Lisa Crispin & Janet Gregory)
I have ordered copies of the Agile testing book for everyone (except Lisa- as she already owns it).
The book is yours to keep.
Assignment of Chapters to SQA engineers
Each chapter will be assigned to one QA engineer; who will read and then present the information to the rest of the group.
Vote on when to present chapters ( a brownbag lunch or during the QA book club meeting.)

Subject: Scrum of Scrums
Body: Removing all recurrences after 14 Nov.

Sr No: As discussed in the last meeting; scrum of scrums will move to once-weekly meetings at the end of the weekly department demo meeting. If the department demo is cancelled; I will send a 15-minute appointment for scrum of scrums on that Wednesday; starting at 10:15.
Scrum of Scrums series for Oct-Dec 2014…
The purpose of this meeting is for each team’s rep to state the following about his/her team’s progress:
1.      What has your team done since we last met?
2.      What will your team do before we meet again?
3.      Is anything slowing your team down or getting in its way?
4.      Are you about to put something in another team’s way?
a.      (Not a standard scrum question; however; it’s important that we communicate these sorts of issues during this meeting.)

Subject: QA Round Table - Status & Process updates
Body: Team;

Sr No: This meeting is required.  Please be on time.  Please make sure to add this time into your sprints so that you are available.
Trying to fix the WebEx.  Please note the new call in information.
1.      Finish Review of:  QA  & Definition of Done
d.      Everyone review the IT definition of done and come to the meeting with what each point means to you and your responsibilities.  This will help us flush out the definition of done for QA.
2.      Metrics that are important/useful to QA
a.      Bugs found in testing versus bugs found after release:  try to keep this down to 2%
b.      Defects logged by severity & priority over time
c.      Deferred defect trends ( including their sev and priority)
d.      Outstanding defects by priority and severity
e.      Code Change metrics/ how many lines of code changed per build; per sprint
g.      New unit tests(code coverage per) per build/per lines of code changed/per sprint
h.      There is a field in JIRA for  test case.  Everyone should be marking the check box as well as putting the test case name in the JIRA item
3.      Estimations:  review of what to include
a.      Time for QA book club
b.      Time for QA book club presentation creation
d.      QA Round table action items
f.      Test cases in stories (# of and test case path in test plan)
•       Future Round table discussions on the following:
Testing is the unregulated art of evaluating the invisible against the ambiguous so as to avoid the unthinkable...

Subject: 1 on 1:  Rion Carter
Body: Please use the following agenda to prepare for our one on ones:

Sr No: Accomplishments & status - a list of current projects; with one or two sentences describing progress and status on each.
2.      Blocked/Waiting on - a list of roadblocks currently stopping projects from progressing.   Describe the roadblock for each in one or two sentences.
3.      To do - a high-level to-do list of what you would like to accomplish in the next week
4.      Areas to develop - areas of development and what activities you have undertaken to develop in those areas.

5.      Quarterly goal tracking - You should be making steady progress toward fulfilling those goals. This is a place to track that progress. Your monthly; quarterly or yearly goals. Note your progress.
6.      Action plans – Record the results of previously established action plans including whether or not they are complete.
Please come to our meeting prepared.
